The CDs-AuNCs assembly was then used to detect amino acids (AAs) in HEPES-NaOH buffer solution, which showed large changes of emission intensity in the presence of cysteine. The emission intensity at 605 nm was quenched gradually, while that at 465 nm was kept almost constant (Fig. 4
                        ). Finally, the emission of AuNCs was quenched near to zero in the presence of 200 μM cysteine. At the same time, the emission intensity at 465 nm was recovered very slightly, which might be affected by other unknown factor. Finally, the intensity ratio of 605 nm–465 nm (I605/I465
                        ) showed an almost linear response to cysteine when being added less than 60 μM, suggesting the assembly was an excellent ratiometric probe for cysteine detection. In addition, the linear response indicated a potential quantitative detection of cysteine by FRET assembly in a wide concentration range (inset of Fig. 4B). Once lowering the concentration of CDs-AuNCs to 5.0 and 10.0 μg/mL, an optimizing limit of detection (LOD) was obtained at 100 nM for cysteine (Fig. S8). The properties of the proposed method (LOD and linear concentration range) were better than or, at least, comparable to the existing cysteine sensors (Table S2). Particularly, the assembly was a ratiometric probe for cysteine, which not only improved the anti-interference (avoided other false-positive answer) and reduced photobleaching but also optimized the accuracy and selectivity of detection. Therefore, the designed novel probe provided an efficient detection of cysteine with a very easy sample preparation and a ratiometric response, supplying a prototype method for accurate cysteine measurement and a potential strategy for clinical diagnosis.
